140
00:05:41.131 --> 00:05:47.542
<b><font color="#FFFF00">♪ ♪</font></b>

141
00:05:52.949 --> 00:05:56.050
You always know you
wanted to become a cop?

142
00:05:56.119 --> 00:05:59.320
Growing up in the hood?
I always hated cops.

143
00:05:59.389 --> 00:06:02.056
Oh. well. then
why'd you become one?

144
00:06:02.125 --> 00:06:02.860
You know the whole

145
00:06:02.861 --> 00:06:04.341
"be the change you
want to see" thing?

146
00:06:04.395 --> 00:06:05.460
Well. uh. yeah.
I figured.

147
00:06:05.529 --> 00:06:07.162
if you can't beat them.
join them.

148
00:06:07.231 --> 00:06:09.865
(chuckles)
What about you?

149
00:06:09.933 --> 00:06:12.968
Same. you know?
Growing up in the hood.

150
00:06:13.037 --> 00:06:14.936
(both laugh)

151
00:06:15.005 --> 00:06:16.838
Where'd you learn Spanish?

152
00:06:16.907 --> 00:06:18.473
Uh. well. I took it
for the job.

153
00:06:18.542 --> 00:06:20.409
I hated feeling
like I was deaf

154
00:06:20.477 --> 00:06:22.711
on so many blocks
of this city.

155
00:06:22.780 --> 00:06:24.646
DISPATCHER:
2-9 Charlie. you have a 24.

156
00:06:24.715 --> 00:06:26.314
Corner of First Street
and Avenue D.

157
00:06:26.383 --> 00:06:29.618
outside the bodega;
victim is Hispanic female.

158
00:06:29.686 --> 00:06:30.897
Caller states that
the witnesses are holding

159
00:06:30.921 --> 00:06:32.287
the perp at this location.

160
00:06:32.356 --> 00:06:33.889
That's the bodega
we just left.

161
00:06:33.957 --> 00:06:35.390
2-9 Charlie.
show us responding.

162
00:06:35.459 --> 00:06:37.259
(siren wailing)

163
00:06:40.864 --> 00:06:43.098
(crowd clamoring)

164
00:06:43.167 --> 00:06:45.200
Police! Back up! Back up.

165
00:06:45.269 --> 00:06:47.847
- We got this. Step aside. step aside.
MAYA: Excuse me. Excuse me.

166
00:06:47.871 --> 00:06:49.115
- Step aside.
- Excuse me. that's enough.

167
00:06:49.139 --> 00:06:51.684
Hey. sir. up.
He just jumped her.

168
00:06:51.685 --> 00:06:52.929
Came out of nowhere
and just jumped her.

169
00:06:52.953 --> 00:06:55.554
Are you serious? After
we gave you a break?

170
00:06:55.623 --> 00:06:56.989
- She had it coming.
- Get up.

171
00:06:57.057 --> 00:06:59.358
Come on. get up. What
are you talking about?

172
00:06:59.426 --> 00:07:03.495
- She runs the store with her husband.
- Okay. come on.

173
00:07:03.564 --> 00:07:05.530
- And they both owe me money!
- No. turn around.

174
00:07:05.599 --> 00:07:07.966
No. you're the cops from before;
you're the ones

175
00:07:08.035 --> 00:07:10.447
who let him go the first time.
- He could have killed that woman.

176
00:07:10.471 --> 00:07:12.649
- Why don't you do your job already. huh?
- You know what?

177
00:07:12.673 --> 00:07:14.907
I want your names.
I want your badge numbers. Now.

178
00:07:17.230 --> 00:07:18.321
Who found the body?

179
00:07:18.322 --> 00:07:20.355
- Those three over there.
- The three of them?

180
00:07:20.424 --> 00:07:21.590
You didn't separate them?

181
00:07:21.658 --> 00:07:22.658
Just alcohol poisoning.

182
00:07:22.693 --> 00:07:23.903
Oh. so you're an M.E. now. too?

183
00:07:23.927 --> 00:07:26.628
You didn't even put
a uniform with them.

184
00:07:26.697 --> 00:07:29.965
What the hell are
you thinking?

185
00:07:30.033 --> 00:07:31.399
Gentlemen. Detective Reagan.

186
00:07:31.468 --> 00:07:32.779
This is my partner.
Detective Baez.

187
00:07:32.803 --> 00:07:34.536
You guys friends
of the deceased?

188
00:07:34.605 --> 00:07:36.438
Not exactly.
but he was a pledge.

189
00:07:36.506 --> 00:07:37.706
So. not friends?

190
00:07:37.774 --> 00:07:39.934
- We just met him last week.
- Know his name was Peter.

191
00:07:39.977 --> 00:07:41.621
- But that's about it.
- So what happened?

192
00:07:41.645 --> 00:07:43.545
When we woke up.
we found him next to the couch.

193
00:07:43.614 --> 00:07:45.914
Looked like he rolled off
and hit his head.

194
00:07:45.983 --> 00:07:46.983
You guys haze pledges?

195
00:07:47.050 --> 00:07:48.361
Force them to drink.
anything like that?

196
00:07:48.385 --> 00:07:50.218
No. uh. we don't haze.

197
00:07:50.287 --> 00:07:52.487
Are any of you even over 21 yet?

198
00:07:52.556 --> 00:07:54.289
- I am.
- So. you bought the alcohol?

199
00:07:54.358 --> 00:07:55.790
No. he brought his own.

200
00:07:57.461 --> 00:07:59.561
And it's not our fault that
he can't hold his liquor.

201
00:07:59.663 --> 00:08:01.396
Look. Officers...
Detectives.

202
00:08:01.465 --> 00:08:04.299
Sure. Detectives. We're sorry.

203
00:08:04.368 --> 00:08:06.334
But this is. like.
a-a victimless crime.

204
00:08:06.403 --> 00:08:08.737
There's a man lying dead
on the floor in there.

205
00:08:08.805 --> 00:08:10.338
That's called a victim.

206
00:08:10.407 --> 00:08:13.541
Okay. you know what I mean--
like. we're not responsible.

207
00:08:13.610 --> 00:08:15.984
Mm-hmm. And how about
you in the back?

208
00:08:15.985 --> 00:08:18.552
- You got a name?
- Uh. Bobby Delaney.

209
00:08:18.621 --> 00:08:20.021
Oh. so you can talk.

210
00:08:20.089 --> 00:08:21.589
Anything you'd like to add?

211
00:08:21.658 --> 00:08:23.816
I mean. we had a keg
and a bowl of jungle juice.

212
00:08:23.840 --> 00:08:25.027
Bobby. shut up.

213
00:08:25.028 --> 00:08:27.295
Guys. there's nothing to hide;
there's no point in lying.

214
00:08:27.363 --> 00:08:29.397
So. did you serve alcohol
or not?

215
00:08:29.465 --> 00:08:31.599
Yes. but it was off-limits
to pledges.

216
00:08:31.668 --> 00:08:33.801
Like I said. he brought his own.

217
00:08:35.638 --> 00:08:38.239
Detective. the victim's
parents are here.

218
00:08:38.308 --> 00:08:40.241
Danny. I can take this one.

219
00:08:40.310 --> 00:08:42.209
I got it. Stay with them.

220
00:08:42.278 --> 00:08:43.344
They know what happened?

221
00:08:43.413 --> 00:08:45.713
They aren't
aware he's dead.

222
00:08:45.782 --> 00:08:48.883
Detective Reagan.

223
00:08:48.951 --> 00:08:51.986
Mr. and Mrs. Jones. I hate
to tell you this. but. uh...

224
00:08:52.055 --> 00:08:54.455
Oh. What...?

225
00:08:54.524 --> 00:08:56.924
No. no. no.
no. no. no...

226
00:08:56.993 --> 00:08:59.093
(sobbing)

227
00:08:59.162 --> 00:09:03.264
Why? No...
(sobbing)

228
00:09:06.102 --> 00:09:08.903
ABETEMARCO:
So. how you doing. Ma?

229
00:09:08.971 --> 00:09:12.707
Oh. it's just a little
scratchy throat. that's all.

230
00:09:12.775 --> 00:09:14.041
Something going around?

231
00:09:14.110 --> 00:09:17.778
No. it's. um...

232
00:09:17.847 --> 00:09:20.014
"endoscopy."

233
00:09:20.083 --> 00:09:22.550
- Endoscopy?
- Yeah. the...

234
00:09:22.618 --> 00:09:25.052
They stick a tube
down your throat.

235
00:09:25.121 --> 00:09:27.722
Yeah. I know what it is. Ma.
but why?

236
00:09:27.790 --> 00:09:30.324
Well. they were testing
for something else.

237
00:09:30.393 --> 00:09:33.194
What do you mean.
something else?

238
00:09:33.262 --> 00:09:36.564
Uh. well. Anthony.
everybody here is old

239
00:09:36.632 --> 00:09:39.166
and they have to give us
a lot of tests.

240
00:09:39.235 --> 00:09:41.802
And what else
have they tested you for?

241
00:09:41.871 --> 00:09:44.872
Oh. my. there's
so many names. uh...

242
00:09:44.941 --> 00:09:46.040
Okay.
I don't know.

243
00:09:46.109 --> 00:09:47.942
I-It's stuff
that happens to you

244
00:09:48.010 --> 00:09:51.278
when you're my age.
- I understand. Ma. I understand.

245
00:09:55.184 --> 00:09:56.884
Uh. excuse me.

246
00:09:58.554 --> 00:09:59.754
Yeah. you two.

247
00:09:59.822 --> 00:10:03.591
We met when. uh. my ma
interviewed. I'm Anthony.

248
00:10:03.659 --> 00:10:05.426
Oh. of course.
I'm Mary O'Donnell.

249
00:10:05.495 --> 00:10:07.194
director of operations.
and this is

250
00:10:07.263 --> 00:10:08.763
Brian Dixon.
our attending physician.

251
00:10:10.733 --> 00:10:13.467
She had an endoscopy.
What for?

252
00:10:13.536 --> 00:10:14.635
She needed the procedure.

253
00:10:14.704 --> 00:10:16.248
She was experiencing
symptoms that sounded like

254
00:10:16.272 --> 00:10:17.750
esophagitis or even
Barrett's disease.

255
00:10:17.774 --> 00:10:20.841
You're comfortable now.
right. Lucille?

256
00:10:20.910 --> 00:10:23.677
Never better. just a little
scratchy throat.

257
00:10:23.746 --> 00:10:25.513
Yeah. I can't believe.
at her age.

258
00:10:25.581 --> 00:10:28.026
you would give her anesthesia.
- We gave her a nasal endoscopy.

259
00:10:28.050 --> 00:10:29.683
It's quick
and we go through the nose.

260
00:10:29.752 --> 00:10:31.018
She was awake the entire time.

261
00:10:31.087 --> 00:10:32.353
And why wasn't I notified?

262
00:10:32.422 --> 00:10:34.455
I'm sorry. sir. but
we have. by definition.

263
00:10:34.524 --> 00:10:36.457
a rather fragile clientele.

264
00:10:36.526 --> 00:10:38.125
We can't always wait
on notifications.

265
00:10:38.194 --> 00:10:41.562
Besides. it was very minor. and
mostly covered by her Medicaid.

266
00:10:41.631 --> 00:10:43.898
But in the future.
I'll make sure to reach out.

267
00:10:45.435 --> 00:10:47.368
Bye-bye...
Thanks.

268
00:10:51.307 --> 00:10:52.473
Look what you've done.

269
00:10:52.542 --> 00:10:54.508
What? What? Ask questions?

270
00:10:54.577 --> 00:10:56.010
Like a cop.

271
00:10:56.078 --> 00:10:59.180
We don't need cops over here.

272
00:11:00.716 --> 00:11:02.450
GORMLEY:
From what I can gather.

273
00:11:02.518 --> 00:11:04.985
it's wagons circling around
Inspector Keith Sullivan.

274
00:11:05.054 --> 00:11:06.487
Whose wagons?

275
00:11:06.556 --> 00:11:08.889
Well. Sully's. obviously.
but some of the other guys

276
00:11:08.958 --> 00:11:11.292
at Firearms and Tactics
and a. and a few

277
00:11:11.360 --> 00:11:12.960
at the Captain's
Benevolent Association.

278
00:11:13.029 --> 00:11:14.995
Saying we was passed over
for affirmative action.

279
00:11:15.064 --> 00:11:16.363
Nothing concrete.

280
00:11:16.432 --> 00:11:18.666
what I'm hearing.
Could just be some guys bitching

281
00:11:18.734 --> 00:11:20.534
about how the old days
were better.

282
00:11:20.603 --> 00:11:22.570
And Sully's old enough
to know better.

283
00:11:22.638 --> 00:11:25.139
Those union guys can wind you up
pretty good. boss.

284
00:11:25.208 --> 00:11:27.408
Well. they're her
union guys. too.

285
00:11:27.477 --> 00:11:28.809
Listen. boss.

286
00:11:28.878 --> 00:11:30.945
Sullivan's old-school.
I'll give you that.

287
00:11:31.013 --> 00:11:33.347
but guys like him are what
built this department.

288
00:11:33.416 --> 00:11:34.682
And I give him credit for it.

289
00:11:34.750 --> 00:11:36.217
and I look
the other way sometimes.

290
00:11:36.285 --> 00:11:38.285
'cause that's how
you and I came up.

291
00:11:38.354 --> 00:11:43.757
But Jane Kimura is the best
candidate for this post. period.

292
00:11:43.826 --> 00:11:46.393
Hopefully. it's just some
barstool bitching

293
00:11:46.462 --> 00:11:47.895
that's making the rounds.

294
00:11:47.964 --> 00:11:48.964
Got a sec?

295
00:11:49.031 --> 00:11:51.398
- Come in.
- I'm getting calls

296
00:11:51.467 --> 00:11:52.867
from the<i> Times</i>
and the<i> Post</i> about

297
00:11:52.935 --> 00:11:54.535
an Inspector Keith Sullivan

298
00:11:54.604 --> 00:11:56.570
crying discrimination
over a promotion?

299
00:11:56.639 --> 00:11:59.874
They're gonna use the media.

300
00:11:59.942 --> 00:12:01.575
First time I'm hearing of it.

301
00:12:01.644 --> 00:12:02.576
What do they got?

302
00:12:02.645 --> 00:12:04.378
Very deep background.

303
00:12:04.447 --> 00:12:07.548
Like someone's running it up
the flagpole.

304
00:12:09.151 --> 00:12:11.085
(sighs)

305
00:12:12.955 --> 00:12:14.221
(elevator bell chimes)

306
00:12:14.290 --> 00:12:15.567
BAEZ: Sounds like
a tragic accident.

307
00:12:15.591 --> 00:12:18.492
Drank too much. trying to
keep up with the older kids.

308
00:12:18.561 --> 00:12:21.562
choked on his own vomit. fell
off the couch. hit his head.

309
00:12:21.631 --> 00:12:24.098
Mm-hmm. Yeah. Hey.
Jack. it's your dad.

310
00:12:24.166 --> 00:12:27.134
Look. give me a call
back. would you? Bye.

311
00:12:27.203 --> 00:12:31.138
That's at least five messages
in as many hours.

312
00:12:31.207 --> 00:12:32.706
I'm just saying.

313
00:12:32.775 --> 00:12:34.642
Well. I just miss him. is all.

314
00:12:34.710 --> 00:12:36.710
What do we got. Doc?

315
00:12:36.779 --> 00:12:39.046
Well. he had over three times
the legal limit of alcohol

316
00:12:39.115 --> 00:12:41.615
in his system when he died.
but that's not what killed him.

317
00:12:41.684 --> 00:12:43.450
What killed him?

318
00:12:43.519 --> 00:12:45.452
Blunt force trauma
to the head.

319
00:12:45.521 --> 00:12:47.254
Could a fall off
the couch do that?

320
00:12:47.323 --> 00:12:49.757
Only if the couch was
about ten stories up.

321
00:12:59.754 --> 00:13:02.764
I understand this may be
cold comfort for you.

322
00:13:02.765 --> 00:13:04.865
but Peter did not
cause his own death.

323
00:13:04.934 --> 00:13:08.102
In fact. this is now
a homicide investigation.

324
00:13:09.672 --> 00:13:11.939
Who would kill a boy like Pete?

325
00:13:12.008 --> 00:13:14.608
We were wondering
if either of you had an idea.

326
00:13:14.677 --> 00:13:16.243
What do you mean. like. enemies?

327
00:13:16.312 --> 00:13:17.992
DANNY: Maybe one
of the fraternity brothers

328
00:13:18.047 --> 00:13:19.980
was particularly
tough on him?

329
00:13:20.049 --> 00:13:21.349
They're tough
on all the pledges.

330
00:13:21.417 --> 00:13:22.516
That's the tradition.

331
00:13:22.931 --> 00:13:24.731
But no one in particular. no.

332
00:13:24.800 --> 00:13:26.132
I never should've...

333
00:13:26.201 --> 00:13:28.334
You never should've what.
Mr. Jones?

334
00:13:28.403 --> 00:13:30.503
BAEZ:
We know this is difficult.

335
00:13:30.572 --> 00:13:33.606
but even something
that seems unconnected...

336
00:13:33.675 --> 00:13:35.241
My husband thought

337
00:13:35.310 --> 00:13:38.144
that the fraternity would be
terrific for Pete.

338
00:13:38.213 --> 00:13:40.880
Pete himself. not so much.

339
00:13:40.949 --> 00:13:41.993
MR. JONES:
He had a hard time

340
00:13:42.017 --> 00:13:44.084
making friends.

341
00:13:44.152 --> 00:13:46.252
Spent a lot of time on his own.

342
00:13:46.321 --> 00:13:49.055
It pained me to see him
alone so much. and I...

343
00:13:49.124 --> 00:13:53.626
My years at a frat were
some of the best of my life.

344
00:13:53.695 --> 00:13:56.229
I guess you could say
I pushed him into it.

345
00:13:56.298 --> 00:13:57.497
It's not your fault.

346
00:13:57.566 --> 00:13:58.732
But he didn't want to do it.

347
00:13:58.800 --> 00:14:00.845
DANNY: You did what you thought
was best for your son.

348
00:14:00.869 --> 00:14:02.802
Nobody joins
a fraternity thinking

349
00:14:02.871 --> 00:14:04.637
they're signing
their own death certificate.

350
00:14:04.706 --> 00:14:07.874
We're gonna do everything we can
to get to the bottom of this.

351
00:14:07.943 --> 00:14:09.008
Thank you.

352
00:14:09.077 --> 00:14:11.111
Officer Collins
will show you out.

353
00:14:11.179 --> 00:14:11.845
Right this way.

354
00:14:11.913 --> 00:14:13.847
We'll be in touch.

355
00:14:16.818 --> 00:14:20.587
Maybe Pete kind of did
bring this on himself.

356
00:14:20.655 --> 00:14:22.388
How?

357
00:14:22.457 --> 00:14:25.658
I'm just saying. he didn't
want to join a fraternity;

358
00:14:25.727 --> 00:14:27.472
then again. he didn't want
to let down his old man.

359
00:14:27.496 --> 00:14:29.028
Maybe he tried to 86 himself.

360
00:14:29.097 --> 00:14:30.597
By what. picking a fight?

361
00:14:30.665 --> 00:14:32.031
We got to start somewhere.

362
00:14:32.100 --> 00:14:33.600
What about this Bobby kid?

363
00:14:33.668 --> 00:14:35.235
- Silent Bob?
- Yeah.

364
00:14:35.303 --> 00:14:37.670
Well. silent is how Pete's
parents just described him.

365
00:14:37.739 --> 00:14:40.373
You think Pete and Bobby
confided in each other?

366
00:14:40.442 --> 00:14:41.508
Birds of a feather.

367
00:14:42.677 --> 00:14:44.210
Let's take a ride.

368
00:14:50.418 --> 00:14:52.685
Hey. can you take a look
at this for me ASAP?

369
00:14:52.754 --> 00:14:54.594
I have to decide
if I'm gonna prosecute on that

370
00:14:54.623 --> 00:14:56.000
by the end of the day.
- All right. sure.

371
00:14:56.024 --> 00:14:57.423
- I'm on it.
- What is all this?

372
00:14:57.492 --> 00:15:00.426
It's nothing.

373
00:15:00.495 --> 00:15:02.595
Doesn't look like nothing.

374
00:15:02.664 --> 00:15:05.265
Blue Skies Retirement Center?
You have something to tell me?

375
00:15:05.333 --> 00:15:07.867
- I'm just looking into them for a pal.
- A pal?

376
00:15:07.936 --> 00:15:10.537
Come on. Anthony. you already
have so much on your plate.

377
00:15:10.605 --> 00:15:13.139
Erin. you got to let me
open a case on this home.

378
00:15:13.208 --> 00:15:15.408
- What? Why?
- Because they gave

379
00:15:15.477 --> 00:15:17.744
my buddy's 80-year-old mother
an endoscopy.

380
00:15:17.813 --> 00:15:19.212
So?

381
00:15:19.281 --> 00:15:20.647
So she didn't ask for it.

382
00:15:20.715 --> 00:15:24.217
They didn't notify my buddy
or her primary doctor.

383
00:15:24.286 --> 00:15:25.552
A-And I called my friend

384
00:15:25.620 --> 00:15:28.121
who works with
the Medicaid inspector general.

385
00:15:28.190 --> 00:15:31.157
and Blue Skies Retirement
Center's on his radar. too.

386
00:15:31.226 --> 00:15:33.493
Okay. so why haven't they
shut them down?

387
00:15:33.562 --> 00:15:34.961
'Cause no one's died yet.

388
00:15:35.030 --> 00:15:37.497
Okay. I'm not following you.

389
00:15:37.566 --> 00:15:39.065
(sighs)

390
00:15:39.134 --> 00:15:40.667
My buddy's me.

391
00:15:40.735 --> 00:15:44.437
And it's my ma they're
running unnecessary tests on.

392
00:15:44.506 --> 00:15:46.639
And you know the thing
about seniors?

393
00:15:46.708 --> 00:15:49.776
It takes one to die
before anyone does anything.

394
00:15:49.845 --> 00:15:51.778
- That's not true.
- Not for you.

395
00:15:51.847 --> 00:15:53.880
You all can provide
for your family.

396
00:15:53.949 --> 00:15:56.282
I can't do that for my ma
on my own.

397
00:15:56.351 --> 00:15:57.650
Well. I see you're upset.

398
00:15:57.719 --> 00:16:00.587
but you can't just start a
crusade because of an endoscopy.

399
00:16:00.655 --> 00:16:03.623
She's my mother.

400
00:16:07.028 --> 00:16:09.963
What do you want me to do?

401
00:16:10.031 --> 00:16:12.165
I'll review your files
instead of going to lunch.

402
00:16:12.234 --> 00:16:14.334
No. I mean about your mother.

403
00:16:17.439 --> 00:16:20.607
Just look the other way.
For now.

404
00:16:20.675 --> 00:16:22.809
Like. we never had
this conversation?

405
00:16:22.878 --> 00:16:24.644
Like that. yeah.

406
00:16:36.758 --> 00:16:38.769
- What the hell happened?
- Well. the kid calmed down.

407
00:16:38.793 --> 00:16:40.538
Even the bodega owner
said we should let him walk.

408
00:16:40.562 --> 00:16:44.364
- He didn't want to press charges.
- We made a judgment call.

409
00:16:44.432 --> 00:16:46.366
Was there a crowd forming

410
00:16:46.434 --> 00:16:48.801
when you first approached the kid?
- Of course. Free show.

411
00:16:48.870 --> 00:16:51.804
Did that have any effect on
your decision to let him walk?

412
00:16:51.873 --> 00:16:54.007
Wait. what are you asking?

413
00:16:54.075 --> 00:16:55.386
Did the crowd have
their phones out filming you?

414
00:16:55.410 --> 00:16:58.544
Yes. Just like every call
on every day.

415
00:16:58.647 --> 00:17:00.013
So?

416
00:17:00.081 --> 00:17:03.216
Are you familiar with what
they call the Ferguson effect?

417
00:17:03.285 --> 00:17:04.328
You think we didn't intervene

418
00:17:04.352 --> 00:17:05.563
because of fear
of repercussions?

419
00:17:05.587 --> 00:17:07.487
- I don't know. I'm asking you.
- No.

420
00:17:07.555 --> 00:17:09.188
We played it by the book.

421
00:17:09.257 --> 00:17:11.758
And yes. we were well
aware we were being filmed

422
00:17:11.826 --> 00:17:13.137
and are aware
that those recordings

423
00:17:13.161 --> 00:17:16.195
can't always tell
the whole story.

424
00:17:16.264 --> 00:17:17.864
What? Come on. Maya.

425
00:17:17.933 --> 00:17:20.700
It was what it was. Two
cops. a neighborhood beef

426
00:17:20.769 --> 00:17:23.002
in a solidly Dominican
neighborhood.

427
00:17:23.071 --> 00:17:24.804
So which is it?

428
00:17:26.841 --> 00:17:29.108
It was a by-the-book stop...

429
00:17:29.177 --> 00:17:31.110
ended up sideways.

430
00:17:31.179 --> 00:17:33.479
I spoke to the store owner.
and he claims

431
00:17:33.548 --> 00:17:36.215
that he begged you two to arrest
the kid. but you refused.

432
00:17:36.284 --> 00:17:38.217
- Well. he's lying.
- That's ridiculous.

433
00:17:38.286 --> 00:17:39.830
I'm just telling you
what he's claiming.

434
00:17:39.854 --> 00:17:41.721
And you believe him and not us?

435
00:17:41.790 --> 00:17:45.425
What I'm saying
is that there's a dispute

436
00:17:45.493 --> 00:17:47.260
as to what happened
on that first call.

437
00:17:47.329 --> 00:17:50.163
What's not in dispute is that
there's a woman in the hospital

438
00:17:50.231 --> 00:17:52.198
on account of that first call.

439
00:17:54.636 --> 00:17:57.103
You both lost your seats
in the car.

440
00:17:57.172 --> 00:18:00.373
You're on a foot patrol until
further notice. That's all.

441
00:18:14.456 --> 00:18:16.389
There he is.

442
00:18:18.460 --> 00:18:20.393
You got a second. Bobby?

443
00:18:20.462 --> 00:18:22.061
I-I told you everything I know.

444
00:18:22.130 --> 00:18:24.163
Everything you know fits
into three sentences?

445
00:18:24.232 --> 00:18:24.652
No.

446
00:18:24.676 --> 00:18:26.437
'Cause that's about all
we've heard from you.

447
00:18:26.868 --> 00:18:29.235
- I need to get to class.
- No.

448
00:18:29.304 --> 00:18:31.738
Our needs come first.
And right now.

449
00:18:31.806 --> 00:18:33.484
we need to know what the hell
happened to Peter Jones.

450
00:18:33.508 --> 00:18:35.141
We're looking at his
death as a homicide.

451
00:18:35.210 --> 00:18:37.643
- I thought it was alcohol poisoning.
- Yeah. so did we.

452
00:18:37.712 --> 00:18:40.413
Until the M.E. showed us
how his skull was caved in.

453
00:18:40.482 --> 00:18:42.515
You know anything
about that?

454
00:18:42.584 --> 00:18:44.951
Hmm?

455
00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:47.787
You know. you seem like
a pretty nice kid. Bobby.

456
00:18:47.856 --> 00:18:50.623
And smart. too. obviously--
you go here.

457
00:18:50.692 --> 00:18:52.003
Life's been pretty good to you.
hasn't it?

458
00:18:52.027 --> 00:18:53.192
How am I doing so far?

459
00:18:53.261 --> 00:18:55.361
- Okay.
- Yeah. well.

460
00:18:55.430 --> 00:18:57.108
here's where your life's
gonna get complicated.

461
00:18:57.132 --> 00:18:59.899
Couple NYPD detectives think
you may know something

462
00:18:59.968 --> 00:19:01.701
about a homicide
they're investigating.

463
00:19:01.770 --> 00:19:04.010
Think you might be holding out.
You know what that means?

464
00:19:04.039 --> 00:19:05.238
I'm not. I swear.

465
00:19:05.306 --> 00:19:06.506
Come on. my partner and I

466
00:19:06.574 --> 00:19:08.319
got X-ray vision; we can see
right through you. kid.

467
00:19:08.343 --> 00:19:10.276
You're holding out. What?

468
00:19:10.345 --> 00:19:11.811
Spit it out.

469
00:19:11.880 --> 00:19:14.814
I was surprised that Pete joined
the frat in the first place.

470
00:19:14.883 --> 00:19:16.382
Surprised how?

471
00:19:16.451 --> 00:19:17.950
He reminded me of my brother...

472
00:19:18.019 --> 00:19:20.153
before my brother
came out of the closet.

473
00:19:20.221 --> 00:19:22.055
- How's that?
- He was acting out.

474
00:19:22.123 --> 00:19:25.324
Like he was trying to distract
people from who he really was.

475
00:19:25.393 --> 00:19:27.360
And he was drinking a ton. too.

476
00:19:27.429 --> 00:19:29.028
Was Pete drinking
last night?

477
00:19:29.097 --> 00:19:30.963
Last time I remember
seeing Peter.

478
00:19:31.032 --> 00:19:33.566
he was going downstairs
to the basement with Colin.

479
00:19:33.635 --> 00:19:34.801
To do what?

480
00:19:34.869 --> 00:19:36.969
- Get a fresh keg.
- Then what happened?

481
00:19:37.038 --> 00:19:40.440
A little later on. I saw Mike
and Colin come up with the keg.

482
00:19:40.508 --> 00:19:42.475
Peter wasn't with them.

483
00:19:42.544 --> 00:19:44.510
Why didn't you
tell us this earlier?

484
00:19:44.579 --> 00:19:46.646
I was drunk.
so it's all kind of blurry.

485
00:19:46.714 --> 00:19:48.114
And when I asked Colin about it.

486
00:19:48.183 --> 00:19:49.760
he told me
that I must have been mistaken.

487
00:19:49.784 --> 00:19:51.851
What makes you so sure
of this now?

488
00:19:53.254 --> 00:19:54.720
There's a video.

489
00:19:54.789 --> 00:19:55.888
What video?

490
00:19:55.957 --> 00:19:58.524
Of the party.
It's a thing with Zeta Phi Tau.

491
00:19:58.593 --> 00:20:00.293
Uh. we take a quick video

492
00:20:00.361 --> 00:20:02.139
of all the parties
right at midnight and share it

493
00:20:02.163 --> 00:20:04.497
with the other chapters. It's
called the Midnight Special.

494
00:20:04.566 --> 00:20:06.499
And you're in charge
of shooting this video?

495
00:20:06.568 --> 00:20:09.235
You still have it?

496
00:20:09.304 --> 00:20:11.537
I noticed when I rewatched it.

497
00:20:11.606 --> 00:20:14.740
It caught Colin and Peter going
downstairs in the background.

498
00:20:18.913 --> 00:20:21.114
- I told you.
- What'd you tell me?

499
00:20:21.182 --> 00:20:22.815
That Sergeant Reagan.

500
00:20:22.884 --> 00:20:24.517
Couple months
with stripes on his sleeve.

501
00:20:24.586 --> 00:20:25.900
he acts like he's sitting up
in One PP with five stars.

502
00:20:25.924 --> 00:20:27.588
Oh. that's not fair.

503
00:20:27.589 --> 00:20:29.555
What's not fair
is a foot post.

504
00:20:29.624 --> 00:20:31.858
- That was pretty harsh.
- "Pretty"?

505
00:20:31.926 --> 00:20:33.626
Why are you
sticking up for him?

506
00:20:33.695 --> 00:20:36.129
He's screwing you over. too.

507
00:20:36.197 --> 00:20:38.297
- He's just doing his job.
- (scoffs) Please.

508
00:20:38.366 --> 00:20:41.334
His job is to second-guess
his cops on the street?

509
00:20:41.402 --> 00:20:43.736
- It went sideways. Maya.
- Not my fault.

510
00:20:43.805 --> 00:20:46.372
No. but we did let that
kid walk pretty fast.

511
00:20:46.441 --> 00:20:49.153
- And you did point out how many
cameras were filming us. so... - Whoa.

512
00:20:49.177 --> 00:20:51.277
- Whoa.
- Hey. I wasn't saying...

513
00:20:51.346 --> 00:20:53.779
I know this precinct and
what works and what doesn't.

514
00:20:53.848 --> 00:20:56.015
which is more than
you or Reagan do.

515
00:20:56.084 --> 00:20:58.451
- Hey. Maya...
- See you when I see you.

516
00:21:00.188 --> 00:21:01.521
(sighs)

517
00:21:13.501 --> 00:21:16.002
Irish neat. glass of ice.

518
00:21:16.070 --> 00:21:17.737
back Sully up.

519
00:21:19.040 --> 00:21:21.741
Of all the gin joints
in all the towns...

520
00:21:21.809 --> 00:21:24.343
Stopped by your house.
They said you'd be here.

521
00:21:24.412 --> 00:21:27.413
When my wife's sisters come
to stay. I generally am.

522
00:21:27.482 --> 00:21:28.681
I met 'em both.

523
00:21:28.750 --> 00:21:30.349
(chuckling):
You made the right move.

524
00:21:30.418 --> 00:21:31.450
(sighs)

525
00:21:31.519 --> 00:21:32.663
Jewish holiday.
eight letters.

526
00:21:32.687 --> 00:21:34.420
begins with "P."

527
00:21:34.489 --> 00:21:37.023
- Passover.
- Exactly.

528
00:21:37.091 --> 00:21:38.958
You didn't get
passed over. Sully.

529
00:21:39.027 --> 00:21:41.027
Firearms and Tactics
are where you belong.

530
00:21:41.095 --> 00:21:44.096
and that's where you're
the most valuable.

531
00:21:46.968 --> 00:21:49.068
Thank you.

532
00:21:49.137 --> 00:21:51.304
She stepped
right over me.

533
00:21:51.372 --> 00:21:54.840
She is the best choice
for chief of training.

534
00:21:54.909 --> 00:21:57.410
Wasn't even close.

535
00:21:57.478 --> 00:21:59.178
It was my turn.

536
00:21:59.247 --> 00:22:01.214
No such thing as turns.

537
00:22:02.383 --> 00:22:04.517
Second time I've
been passed over.

538
00:22:04.586 --> 00:22:06.953
First. Hostage Negotiation.

539
00:22:07.021 --> 00:22:09.155
Oh. give me a break. Sully.

540
00:22:09.224 --> 00:22:10.489
(laughs)

541
00:22:10.558 --> 00:22:13.826
Hostage Negotiation was never
on the table for you.

542
00:22:13.895 --> 00:22:16.062
I mean. you talking
a jumper down?

543
00:22:16.130 --> 00:22:18.764
"Get the hell off that ledge.
or I'll push you off myself."

544
00:22:20.034 --> 00:22:22.368
Time was. toughness
was an asset.

545
00:22:22.437 --> 00:22:24.604
Still is. Comes in all
shapes and sizes.

546
00:22:24.672 --> 00:22:26.072
Oh. give me a break.

547
00:22:26.140 --> 00:22:28.741
Oh. come on. Sully.

548
00:22:28.810 --> 00:22:31.277
(sighs)
We've known each other too long.

549
00:22:31.346 --> 00:22:33.279
Let's not do this.

550
00:22:34.482 --> 00:22:37.450
I'd make a great
chief of training. Frank.

551
00:22:37.518 --> 00:22:39.752
And you know that.

552
00:22:39.821 --> 00:22:42.989
But it's 2018.
and the new wisdom is

553
00:22:43.057 --> 00:22:44.890
a younger Asian female's
a better candidate

554
00:22:44.959 --> 00:22:47.827
than an older white guy.

555
00:22:47.895 --> 00:22:49.962
Call it what it is.

556
00:22:53.101 --> 00:22:57.737
When you were my son Danny's
first C.O.. he came to me.

557
00:22:57.805 --> 00:22:59.372
Did you know that?

558
00:22:59.440 --> 00:23:02.942
Yeah. he said. "Dad.
this guy Sully's a good cop.

559
00:23:03.011 --> 00:23:06.145
but maybe he's too tough on us."

560
00:23:06.214 --> 00:23:09.215
You're learning the ropes.
sometimes you get rope burns.

561
00:23:09.284 --> 00:23:10.950
He did two tours in Iraq.

562
00:23:11.019 --> 00:23:13.119
He knew the ropes.

563
00:23:13.187 --> 00:23:14.453
And your point is?

564
00:23:14.522 --> 00:23:17.723
If Danny Reagan says you
are too tough a cop.

565
00:23:17.792 --> 00:23:19.492
it's like Keith Richards saying

566
00:23:19.560 --> 00:23:23.195
you have a substance
abuse problem.

567
00:23:23.264 --> 00:23:25.331
You really should listen.

568
00:23:30.371 --> 00:23:33.673
I hate to see you
bending to these winds.

569
00:23:33.741 --> 00:23:36.776
And I'd hate to lose you
from this department.

570
00:23:43.584 --> 00:23:45.718
Lot of good years left.

571
00:23:56.139 --> 00:23:58.339
(raucous cheering. clamoring)

572
00:23:59.976 --> 00:24:02.947
Another guy chugging.

573
00:24:02.948 --> 00:24:04.681
What she calls dancing.

574
00:24:04.749 --> 00:24:06.282
What are we looking for?

575
00:24:06.351 --> 00:24:08.384
Them. That's who
we're looking for.

576
00:24:08.453 --> 00:24:09.453
Can you zoom in?

577
00:24:11.857 --> 00:24:12.956
DANNY:
There's Pete.

578
00:24:13.024 --> 00:24:14.390
as promised.

579
00:24:14.459 --> 00:24:15.459
Anything else?

580
00:24:15.527 --> 00:24:17.327
Did you find anything
in their social media?

581
00:24:18.597 --> 00:24:20.363
I did notice one thing.

582
00:24:20.432 --> 00:24:22.899
This kid. Mike.
has Colin in all of his posts.

583
00:24:22.968 --> 00:24:26.736
But if you look at Colin's page.
you'd never know Mike existed.

584
00:24:30.108 --> 00:24:33.209
Officer. I've already told you
everything I know.

585
00:24:33.278 --> 00:24:35.578
That's the problem. Jose.
I don't think you did.

586
00:24:35.647 --> 00:24:36.913
What do you mean?

587
00:24:36.982 --> 00:24:39.048
I think you were afraid
what might happen to you.

588
00:24:39.117 --> 00:24:40.683
and so you lied to me and said

589
00:24:40.752 --> 00:24:42.597
that you asked those officers
to arrest that kid.

590
00:24:42.621 --> 00:24:43.953
Why would I do that?

591
00:24:44.022 --> 00:24:46.256
Because you're employing Luis
without paying him.

592
00:24:46.324 --> 00:24:48.091
What are you saying. Officer?

593
00:24:48.160 --> 00:24:49.192
That he's here illegally.

594
00:24:49.261 --> 00:24:50.560
that you and your wife
knew that.

595
00:24:50.629 --> 00:24:52.262
and that you were
making him work for you

596
00:24:52.330 --> 00:24:53.441
under threat of
informing ICE.

597
00:24:53.465 --> 00:24:54.876
- You got it all wrong.
- Forcing someone

598
00:24:54.900 --> 00:24:56.511
to work for nothing.
that's called slavery here.

599
00:24:56.535 --> 00:24:58.635
It's been illegal
for about 150 years.

600
00:25:00.338 --> 00:25:02.739
We made him sandwiches.
That's a kind of pay.

601
00:25:02.807 --> 00:25:05.074
I'd like you to come down
to the station

602
00:25:05.143 --> 00:25:06.609
and clear this up for me.

603
00:25:07.913 --> 00:25:10.013
Can you give me. uh.
ten minutes to close up?

604
00:25:10.081 --> 00:25:11.121
I'll give you two minutes.

605
00:25:11.183 --> 00:25:13.383
- Thank you. Officer.
- It's Sergeant.

606
00:25:14.486 --> 00:25:15.486
Sergeant.

607
00:25:24.729 --> 00:25:27.664
♪ ♪

608
00:25:27.732 --> 00:25:29.399
Sure. sure.

609
00:25:29.467 --> 00:25:31.834
Yeah. I-I remember you.

610
00:25:31.903 --> 00:25:33.002
Henry.

611
00:25:33.071 --> 00:25:34.971
Well. it's been a long time.

612
00:25:35.040 --> 00:25:36.206
It sure has.

613
00:25:36.274 --> 00:25:38.041
How are you?

614
00:25:38.109 --> 00:25:40.176
- About as well as can be expected.
- Good.

615
00:25:40.245 --> 00:25:41.878
How are they treating you here?

616
00:25:41.947 --> 00:25:43.880
Well. you know.
it's pretty good.

617
00:25:43.949 --> 00:25:47.483
But. uh. they give us
so many tests.

618
00:25:47.552 --> 00:25:49.185
Really?

619
00:25:49.254 --> 00:25:51.554
You know. like they say.

620
00:25:51.623 --> 00:25:53.656
old age is not for wimps.

621
00:25:53.725 --> 00:25:55.658
(both laugh)

622
00:25:59.264 --> 00:26:00.597
Oh. my gosh.

623
00:26:00.665 --> 00:26:01.598
What?

624
00:26:01.666 --> 00:26:03.967
I haven't seen him in 20 years.

625
00:26:04.035 --> 00:26:05.868
- Who?
- Reading the paper.

626
00:26:05.937 --> 00:26:07.370
right over there.

627
00:26:07.439 --> 00:26:09.472
LUCILLE:
Jack Kehoe.

628
00:26:09.541 --> 00:26:11.641
- Excuse me a minute?
- Sure.

629
00:26:14.379 --> 00:26:15.712
Jack.

630
00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:17.213
Jack Kehoe?

631
00:26:17.282 --> 00:26:18.881
Yes?

632
00:26:18.950 --> 00:26:20.650
Henry Reagan.

633
00:26:22.053 --> 00:26:23.753
Henry.
(both laugh)

634
00:26:23.822 --> 00:26:24.887
How the hell are you?

635
00:26:24.956 --> 00:26:26.322
Well. a lot better than you.

636
00:26:26.391 --> 00:26:28.324
from the looks of your
dance partner there.

637
00:26:28.393 --> 00:26:30.860
(both laugh)

638
00:26:32.097 --> 00:26:34.364
So. uh. how you doing?

639
00:26:38.003 --> 00:26:39.369
Maybe this was
a bad idea.

640
00:26:39.437 --> 00:26:41.415
That thought applies to
about five different things

641
00:26:41.439 --> 00:26:42.739
in my mind right now.

642
00:26:42.807 --> 00:26:43.840
Whoa.

643
00:26:43.908 --> 00:26:46.843
So. would you mind
being more specific?

644
00:26:46.911 --> 00:26:49.012
You coming over
to the 2-9.

645
00:26:49.080 --> 00:26:52.181
Oh. That wasn't even
one of the five.

646
00:26:52.250 --> 00:26:54.784
Eddie. I'm the boss now.
That's gonna come up.

647
00:26:54.853 --> 00:26:57.520
Not always in a good way.
Almost never in a good way.

648
00:26:57.589 --> 00:26:59.155
You took me out
of the car.

649
00:26:59.224 --> 00:27:00.890
and you put me
on a foot post.

650
00:27:00.959 --> 00:27:03.459
Eddie. Eddie.

651
00:27:03.528 --> 00:27:06.029
- (sighs)
- I busted both of you.

652
00:27:06.097 --> 00:27:08.131
Okay. what was I gonna do.
her and not you?

653
00:27:08.199 --> 00:27:09.465
Or neither?

654
00:27:09.534 --> 00:27:11.367
Let me guess.
She's one of those.

655
00:27:11.436 --> 00:27:13.002
the cell phone
cameras come on.

656
00:27:13.071 --> 00:27:14.915
and she starts playing defense
instead of offense.

657
00:27:14.939 --> 00:27:16.372
Am I right?

658
00:27:16.441 --> 00:27:18.274
I'll take that as a yes.

659
00:27:18.343 --> 00:27:20.543
You know what?
You're a sergeant. not a mystic.

660
00:27:20.612 --> 00:27:21.978
Don't get ahead of yourself.

661
00:27:22.047 --> 00:27:23.713
Eddie. the foot post
was a little harsh.

662
00:27:23.782 --> 00:27:25.782
but it had to be.
- Why?

663
00:27:25.850 --> 00:27:28.418
So that you and Maya would pull
a common enemy out of this.

664
00:27:28.486 --> 00:27:31.054
You guys would have a chance
to bond as partners on the job.

665
00:27:31.122 --> 00:27:32.322
I defended you.

666
00:27:32.390 --> 00:27:34.924
I think that was a mistake. too.

667
00:27:34.959 --> 00:27:36.859
- "Too"? (scoffs)
- I'm the boss.

668
00:27:36.928 --> 00:27:38.528
Nobody likes the boss.

669
00:27:38.596 --> 00:27:41.297
Eddie. half the fun of the job
is making fun of the boss.

670
00:27:41.366 --> 00:27:43.366
Oh. I look forward
to catching up on that.

671
00:27:44.736 --> 00:27:46.714
Seriously. if we're gonna
turn this precinct around

672
00:27:46.738 --> 00:27:48.404
and you're my agent
on the ground.

673
00:27:48.473 --> 00:27:50.273
there's gonna be cross fire.

674
00:27:50.342 --> 00:27:51.941
Is that what we're doing?

675
00:27:52.010 --> 00:27:53.476
Turning the whole precinct
around?

676
00:27:53.545 --> 00:27:55.812
Yeah. one cop at a time.

677
00:28:09.127 --> 00:28:10.727
It work?

678
00:28:10.795 --> 00:28:12.695
Yeah. like a charm.

679
00:28:12.764 --> 00:28:13.963
What'd you get?

680
00:28:14.032 --> 00:28:16.466
A lot of selfies
with my new old friends.

681
00:28:16.534 --> 00:28:17.867
I meant...

682
00:28:17.936 --> 00:28:21.270
It's like they're running
a placebo clinic in there.

683
00:28:21.339 --> 00:28:25.308
Guys walking around with I.V.
bags full of saline solution

684
00:28:25.377 --> 00:28:27.977
they're told
is lifesaving meds.

685
00:28:28.046 --> 00:28:29.612
And getting
billed as that.

686
00:28:29.681 --> 00:28:31.080
I'm guessing.

687
00:28:31.149 --> 00:28:33.716
And the attending
physician. Brian.

688
00:28:33.785 --> 00:28:36.085
You know he's a Brian Junior?

689
00:28:36.154 --> 00:28:37.253
So?

690
00:28:37.322 --> 00:28:39.255
His father was a doctor.

691
00:28:39.324 --> 00:28:41.391
Passed away nine months ago.

692
00:28:41.459 --> 00:28:43.693
One of the old-timers
told me that he thought

693
00:28:43.762 --> 00:28:46.729
Brian Junior's degree
was in nursing.

694
00:28:46.798 --> 00:28:49.565
So. the doc's not even a doc?

695
00:28:49.634 --> 00:28:50.666
Looks like that.

696
00:28:52.370 --> 00:28:53.669
Bastards.

697
00:28:53.738 --> 00:28:55.371
Don't drive angry.

698
00:28:55.440 --> 00:28:57.707
I'd like to make it home.

699
00:29:00.445 --> 00:29:02.712
I forgot how lucky I am.

700
00:29:05.950 --> 00:29:07.450
(sighs)

701
00:29:07.519 --> 00:29:09.318
All right. here we go.

702
00:29:09.387 --> 00:29:11.154
(cheering)

703
00:29:11.222 --> 00:29:13.322
You and Sean do this
all yourselves?

704
00:29:13.391 --> 00:29:14.391
- That's right.
- Wow.

705
00:29:14.426 --> 00:29:15.358
We made all Jack's favorites

706
00:29:15.427 --> 00:29:17.393
in celebration of
his birthday.

707
00:29:17.462 --> 00:29:18.594
Which is today.
as we know.

708
00:29:18.663 --> 00:29:19.595
We know.
That's right.

709
00:29:19.664 --> 00:29:20.897
Everybody send cards?
ALL: Yes.

710
00:29:20.965 --> 00:29:22.276
NICKY: We should all
FaceTime him after we eat.

711
00:29:22.300 --> 00:29:23.332
DANNY:
Definitely.

712
00:29:23.401 --> 00:29:24.645
Good idea.
ERIN: First birthday away.

713
00:29:24.669 --> 00:29:26.169
It's happy and sad.

714
00:29:26.237 --> 00:29:27.336
Yeah.

715
00:29:27.405 --> 00:29:29.183
Nah. his age. you get to be
too old for birthdays.

716
00:29:29.207 --> 00:29:30.584
It becomes about your parents
being too gooey.

717
00:29:30.608 --> 00:29:33.042
You cashed the checks.
as I remember.

718
00:29:33.111 --> 00:29:35.845
And Mom made me wear the
pointed hat well into my 20s.

719
00:29:35.914 --> 00:29:37.413
Well. small price to pay.

720
00:29:37.482 --> 00:29:38.826
- Pictures. please.
ERIN: Oh. yeah.

721
00:29:38.850 --> 00:29:40.383
Photo album's in
the living room.

722
00:29:40.452 --> 00:29:42.285
Is this varmint or critter?

723
00:29:42.353 --> 00:29:45.087
Chicken fried steak
and chicken fried chicken.

724
00:29:45.156 --> 00:29:46.367
FRANK: Oh.
- Yeah. but you got to put

725
00:29:46.391 --> 00:29:47.768
the sausage gravy on it
for the full effect.

726
00:29:47.792 --> 00:29:50.359
What effect is that.
a full cardiac arrest?

727
00:29:50.428 --> 00:29:51.928
- Ha ha.
- Very funny.

728
00:29:51.996 --> 00:29:52.996
Are there any vegetables?

729
00:29:53.031 --> 00:29:54.530
Onion rings.

730
00:29:54.599 --> 00:29:56.444
- There you go. - French fries.
- You got your potato.

731
00:29:56.468 --> 00:29:59.635
And there's pickles. And ketchup
is kind of a vegetable. right?

732
00:29:59.704 --> 00:30:00.744
SEAN: Yeah.
FRANK: Perfect.

733
00:30:00.805 --> 00:30:01.805
Kind of.

734
00:30:01.873 --> 00:30:04.540
I don't want to hear
complaining.

735
00:30:07.145 --> 00:30:08.544
I'm not complaining. Pop.

736
00:30:08.613 --> 00:30:11.380
I'm hearing snark.
I don't like snark.

737
00:30:11.449 --> 00:30:12.548
Pops. we were just joking.

738
00:30:12.617 --> 00:30:15.084
What we should all be
is grateful.

739
00:30:16.287 --> 00:30:17.954
What's up. Pop?

740
00:30:19.057 --> 00:30:20.590
(sighs)

741
00:30:20.658 --> 00:30:22.959
I visited a nursing home
the other day.

742
00:30:23.027 --> 00:30:25.161
It's just so depressing.

743
00:30:25.230 --> 00:30:26.529
Who'd you visit?

744
00:30:27.832 --> 00:30:28.931
Ronnie.

745
00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:30.733
Ronnie. Oh. where's Ronnie?

746
00:30:30.802 --> 00:30:33.135
The. uh. Sunset something.

747
00:30:33.204 --> 00:30:35.171
Blue Skies?

748
00:30:35.240 --> 00:30:36.772
No. the Sunset
or Sunrise something.

749
00:30:38.309 --> 00:30:42.645
And I was starkly aware
of how good I have it.

750
00:30:42.714 --> 00:30:45.648
How good we all have it.
having each other.

751
00:30:47.418 --> 00:30:50.286
I'm... I'm just feeling...

752
00:30:50.355 --> 00:30:53.389
especially blessed.

753
00:30:53.458 --> 00:30:55.491
That's all I'm gonna say.
Pass the meat. please.

754
00:30:55.560 --> 00:30:58.127
- Critter or varmint?
- Both. thanks.

755
00:30:58.196 --> 00:30:59.328
Grace first.

756
00:30:59.397 --> 00:31:01.364
Bless us. O Lord.

757
00:31:01.432 --> 00:31:03.799
ALL: For these. thy gifts.
which we are about to receive

758
00:31:03.868 --> 00:31:07.470
from thy bounty.
through Christ. our Lord. Amen.

759
00:31:08.369 --> 00:31:09.801
FRANK: Okay.
Varmint or critter?

760
00:31:20.130 --> 00:31:22.563
Okay.

761
00:31:22.632 --> 00:31:24.599
I talked to Sully.

762
00:31:24.668 --> 00:31:26.935
I think I made a dent.

763
00:31:27.003 --> 00:31:30.705
but if I had a nickel every time
I liked what I thought...

764
00:31:30.774 --> 00:31:32.476
Would you like
to postpone?

765
00:31:32.477 --> 00:31:33.877
Would you?

766
00:31:33.946 --> 00:31:35.979
No.

767
00:31:36.048 --> 00:31:39.449
Look. here's all
you need to know.

768
00:31:39.518 --> 00:31:41.618
Even if Sully decides
to bring the suit.

769
00:31:41.687 --> 00:31:44.554
that's nothing compared
to what you're in for--

770
00:31:44.623 --> 00:31:46.656
the actual job.

771
00:31:46.725 --> 00:31:48.792
- From?
- From all sides.

772
00:31:48.860 --> 00:31:51.061
And this high up.

773
00:31:51.129 --> 00:31:54.598
you can't just give 'em rips
or brace 'em in the locker room.

774
00:31:54.666 --> 00:31:57.567
Locker room's off-
limits to me anyway.

775
00:31:59.705 --> 00:32:01.805
(sighs)

776
00:32:01.873 --> 00:32:04.874
I hope you know what I'm saying.

777
00:32:04.943 --> 00:32:07.377
I think so.

778
00:32:07.446 --> 00:32:11.047
I need to know for sure.

779
00:32:11.116 --> 00:32:14.951
Gook. Chink. Nip.

780
00:32:15.020 --> 00:32:17.621
a Charlie. slant.

781
00:32:17.689 --> 00:32:20.056
slope. Tokyo Rose.

782
00:32:20.125 --> 00:32:23.126
(laughs)

783
00:32:23.195 --> 00:32:26.029
Heard 'em all before I was ten.

784
00:32:26.098 --> 00:32:29.099
You didn't hear those words
in my department.

785
00:32:29.167 --> 00:32:32.235
Nope. but even if I did.

786
00:32:32.304 --> 00:32:34.337
it wouldn't affect
how I do my job.

787
00:32:35.707 --> 00:32:38.074
Because you've had
a very thick skin

788
00:32:38.143 --> 00:32:41.144
since even before
the fourth grade.

789
00:32:41.213 --> 00:32:43.146
Pretty much.

790
00:32:44.483 --> 00:32:47.851
Let's say a Sully--

791
00:32:47.919 --> 00:32:52.055
let's say he gave you
an "attaboy" on the promotion.

792
00:32:52.124 --> 00:32:56.292
Would that also bounce
right off that thick skin?

793
00:32:56.361 --> 00:32:57.560
What do you mean?

794
00:32:57.629 --> 00:32:59.562
Or...

795
00:32:59.631 --> 00:33:02.565
would it feel good.

796
00:33:02.634 --> 00:33:05.969
coming from some
old-school Irish mug?

797
00:33:15.580 --> 00:33:17.213
It would feel good.

798
00:33:24.056 --> 00:33:27.057
Because it came
from a fellow cop.

799
00:33:37.135 --> 00:33:39.669
Officer Janko. Officer Thomas.
thanks for stopping by.

800
00:33:39.738 --> 00:33:42.338
I wasn't aware
we had a choice.

801
00:33:42.407 --> 00:33:44.318
Know it's been a tough week.
I'd like to apologize

802
00:33:44.342 --> 00:33:45.753
if you perceived
that I didn't have your back.

803
00:33:45.777 --> 00:33:47.844
'Cause you didn't?

804
00:33:48.810 --> 00:33:51.075
They were working Luis
without any pay.

805
00:33:51.076 --> 00:33:52.442
He's here illegally.

806
00:33:52.511 --> 00:33:54.444
Both of them backed down

807
00:33:54.513 --> 00:33:55.991
because nobody
in that neighborhood wants

808
00:33:56.015 --> 00:33:57.681
to bring their beefs
into the precinct.

809
00:33:57.750 --> 00:33:59.683
Could have
told you that.

810
00:33:59.752 --> 00:34:02.352
So why'd he lie. the owner?
Saying he asked us

811
00:34:02.421 --> 00:34:03.620
to arrest Luis?

812
00:34:03.689 --> 00:34:05.100
Panicked it'd look like
he didn't protect his wife.

813
00:34:05.124 --> 00:34:06.456
He tried

814
00:34:06.525 --> 00:34:08.925
to walk back what happened
by stepping all over you guys.

815
00:34:08.994 --> 00:34:10.193
Oh.

816
00:34:11.430 --> 00:34:14.131
So... we're good?

817
00:34:14.199 --> 00:34:16.133
Almost.

818
00:34:17.321 --> 00:34:20.155
Your instincts. your actions you
take out there can't be driven

819
00:34:20.156 --> 00:34:23.090
by whether or not you're being
recorded. not on my watch.

820
00:34:25.707 --> 00:34:26.651
They weren't.

821
00:34:26.652 --> 00:34:27.984
Didn't enter into it.

822
00:34:28.052 --> 00:34:30.786
Can't help but enter into it--

823
00:34:30.855 --> 00:34:35.491
a crowd. these streets.
this climate.

824
00:34:35.560 --> 00:34:37.260
I hear you.

825
00:34:37.328 --> 00:34:38.895
Copy that.

826
00:34:38.963 --> 00:34:41.397
There's a whole review system
in place

827
00:34:41.466 --> 00:34:44.066
for cases exactly like this.
so. trust it.

828
00:34:44.135 --> 00:34:45.501
All right?

829
00:34:45.570 --> 00:34:47.570
You guys are back on wheels.
so get out of here.

830
00:34:47.639 --> 00:34:48.804
Sarge. if I may?

831
00:34:48.873 --> 00:34:50.806
Um... thank you.

832
00:34:50.875 --> 00:34:53.409
My old sergeant--
he wouldn't have taken the time.

833
00:34:53.478 --> 00:34:56.212
Just doing my job.

834
00:35:02.954 --> 00:35:04.921
You ever go down
to the basement with Peter?

835
00:35:04.989 --> 00:35:06.088
I already told you. no.

836
00:35:06.157 --> 00:35:07.757
That's interesting.
'cause we have video

837
00:35:07.825 --> 00:35:10.726
of you going downstairs
to the basement<i> with</i> Pete

838
00:35:10.795 --> 00:35:12.094
and coming upstairs without him.

839
00:35:12.163 --> 00:35:13.529
Oh. so you're
trusting Bobby now?

840
00:35:13.598 --> 00:35:14.830
He's a pathological liar.

841
00:35:14.899 --> 00:35:15.899
The tape don't lie. kid.

842
00:35:15.967 --> 00:35:17.244
and get your hands
back on the table.

843
00:35:17.268 --> 00:35:18.268
Don't call me "kid."

844
00:35:18.336 --> 00:35:20.670
You realize that if you two
were hazing him.

845
00:35:20.738 --> 00:35:22.950
you're both gonna be facing
second-degree murder charges.

846
00:35:22.974 --> 00:35:25.074
right?
- Well. we weren't.

847
00:35:25.143 --> 00:35:27.009
BAEZ:
<i>It tough being away</i>

848
00:35:27.078 --> 00:35:28.544
from your family?

849
00:35:28.613 --> 00:35:30.212
Yeah. of course.
but the frat helps.

850
00:35:30.281 --> 00:35:32.381
and they're like my family.

851
00:35:32.450 --> 00:35:33.894
You sure have a funny way
of showing it.

852
00:35:33.918 --> 00:35:36.352
For the millionth time.
we did nothing wrong.

853
00:35:36.421 --> 00:35:37.620
We don't haze.

854
00:35:37.689 --> 00:35:39.088
Why are you covering for Colin?

855
00:35:39.157 --> 00:35:41.290
What do you mean?

856
00:35:41.359 --> 00:35:42.591
Is he your best friend?

857
00:35:42.660 --> 00:35:44.071
- Detective... this going somewhere?
- Yes!

858
00:35:44.095 --> 00:35:45.561
He doesn't post
any photos with you.

859
00:35:45.630 --> 00:35:46.796
Does that bother you?

860
00:35:46.864 --> 00:35:48.631
What are you trying to say?

861
00:35:48.700 --> 00:35:51.267
You think he'd face years
in jail for you?

862
00:35:52.804 --> 00:35:54.870
I don't know.

863
00:35:54.939 --> 00:35:56.572
Because that's what's
happening here.

864
00:35:56.641 --> 00:35:58.140
The more you continue to lie.

865
00:35:58.209 --> 00:35:59.942
the more trouble
you're gonna be in.

866
00:36:00.011 --> 00:36:02.111
Ah. Well. this just
got a little bit easier.

867
00:36:02.180 --> 00:36:03.312
What happened?

868
00:36:03.381 --> 00:36:04.780
Colin told the truth.

869
00:36:04.849 --> 00:36:06.916
- He did?
- Yeah. he did.

870
00:36:06.985 --> 00:36:10.086
You two were hazing Peter.
you lost control.

871
00:36:10.154 --> 00:36:11.954
He tried to stop you.
but he couldn't.

872
00:36:12.023 --> 00:36:14.724
and then you blackmailed
him to cover for you.

873
00:36:17.862 --> 00:36:20.129
- He didn't say that.
- He did.

874
00:36:20.198 --> 00:36:21.564
- He wouldn't.
- He would.

875
00:36:21.632 --> 00:36:23.466
Got a statement right here.

876
00:36:23.534 --> 00:36:25.501
Then hand it over.

877
00:36:25.570 --> 00:36:27.970
Just a second.
Can I talk to you for a minute?

878
00:36:33.211 --> 00:36:35.144
My guy's lawyer's
not as sharp.

879
00:36:35.213 --> 00:36:37.146
Let's try this
again over here.

880
00:36:38.549 --> 00:36:41.617
Well. I hate to break it to you.
but your buddy Mike flipped

881
00:36:41.686 --> 00:36:42.852
and turned you in.

882
00:36:42.920 --> 00:36:44.186
Colin. don't say a word.

883
00:36:44.255 --> 00:36:45.621
You're looking at

884
00:36:45.690 --> 00:36:47.023
some serious time.<i> kid.</i>

885
00:36:47.091 --> 00:36:49.425
- He would never.
- Well. he did.

886
00:36:49.494 --> 00:36:52.194
In fact. he just finished giving
my partner his statement.

887
00:36:52.263 --> 00:36:54.663
I did nothing wrong.

888
00:36:54.732 --> 00:36:57.533
I... I was just trying
to be nice to that loser.

889
00:36:57.602 --> 00:36:58.160
I'm sure you were.

890
00:36:58.184 --> 00:37:00.347
No. I just took him down to the
basement to give him some coke.

891
00:37:00.371 --> 00:37:02.138
Coke. Oh. well.
I guess we'll be adding

892
00:37:02.207 --> 00:37:03.784
"criminal possession"
to your list of charges.

893
00:37:03.808 --> 00:37:05.422
No. I am the victim here.
don't you see?

894
00:37:05.446 --> 00:37:06.577
No. I don't see.

895
00:37:06.578 --> 00:37:09.245
I was just trying to be nice to
that fairy. and what does he do?

896
00:37:10.548 --> 00:37:12.615
Oh.

897
00:37:12.684 --> 00:37:15.785
Pete made a move on you.
and you didn't like it?

898
00:37:15.854 --> 00:37:18.654
- Colin. enough.
- He tried to kiss me. okay?

899
00:37:18.723 --> 00:37:21.123
Like I was some chick.
He was grabbing at me.

900
00:37:21.192 --> 00:37:22.458
And then what happened?

901
00:37:22.527 --> 00:37:24.660
- I lost it! Who wouldn't?
- Careful. Detective.

902
00:37:24.729 --> 00:37:26.607
My client is claiming he was
the victim of a sexual assault.

903
00:37:26.631 --> 00:37:27.997
He tried to kiss you.
you lost it.

904
00:37:28.066 --> 00:37:30.633
and what happened next?!
I shoved him!

905
00:37:30.702 --> 00:37:32.635
I shoved him away.

906
00:37:35.573 --> 00:37:37.306
You shoved him away.

907
00:37:37.375 --> 00:37:38.375
and he fell down.

908
00:37:38.443 --> 00:37:41.711
and he never got back up again.
did he?

909
00:37:41.779 --> 00:37:43.646
It wasn't my fault.

910
00:37:43.715 --> 00:37:46.115
He's the victim of
a sexual assault.

911
00:37:46.184 --> 00:37:48.751
- He had the right...
- He can tell that to the judge.

912
00:37:49.854 --> 00:37:52.321
Get on your feet...<i> kid.</i>

913
00:37:52.390 --> 00:37:54.323
Get up!

914
00:37:56.294 --> 00:37:58.227
(indistinct chatter)

915
00:38:06.437 --> 00:38:08.371
HENRY:
I think Erin

916
00:38:08.439 --> 00:38:10.606
suspects I had something
to do with this.

917
00:38:10.675 --> 00:38:12.842
All I said was I
used an undercover.

918
00:38:12.911 --> 00:38:14.877
Yeah. I know. but...

919
00:38:14.946 --> 00:38:16.879
I kind of...

920
00:38:16.948 --> 00:38:19.015
At dinner on Sunday.
I inadvertently...

921
00:38:19.083 --> 00:38:20.182
Inadvertently?

922
00:38:20.251 --> 00:38:22.184
I didn't mean to.

923
00:38:22.253 --> 00:38:24.186
But she's like a ferret.

924
00:38:24.255 --> 00:38:27.757
- Well. you know what she's like.
- Come clean?

925
00:38:27.825 --> 00:38:29.158
No.

926
00:38:29.227 --> 00:38:32.161
It's bound to come up
eventually. this goes to trial.

927
00:38:32.230 --> 00:38:35.298
I thought maybe
we could tell her together.

928
00:38:35.366 --> 00:38:37.500
Strength in numbers?

929
00:38:37.568 --> 00:38:39.502
You got it.

930
00:38:39.570 --> 00:38:41.504
(chuckles)

931
00:38:41.572 --> 00:38:44.573
So. did you find a place
for your ma?

932
00:38:44.642 --> 00:38:46.909
- Yeah.
- Where?

933
00:38:46.978 --> 00:38:49.779
With me. See how it goes.

934
00:38:51.349 --> 00:38:53.282
Good for you. Anthony.

935
00:38:56.587 --> 00:38:58.621
GORMLEY: When your
name is called.

936
00:38:58.690 --> 00:39:00.456
you walk up the aisle
on the right.

937
00:39:00.525 --> 00:39:01.724
Stage right or my right?

938
00:39:01.793 --> 00:39:03.059
Uh. your right.

939
00:39:03.127 --> 00:39:05.127
You walk up to the first
deputy commissioner.

940
00:39:05.196 --> 00:39:06.462
and you shake his hand.

941
00:39:06.531 --> 00:39:08.764
Then when the master
of ceremonies states.

942
00:39:08.833 --> 00:39:12.568
"I now introduce the
new chief of training."

943
00:39:12.637 --> 00:39:14.403
you face the commissioner

944
00:39:14.472 --> 00:39:16.439
and salute.

945
00:39:18.176 --> 00:39:20.343
Inspector Sullivan
is asking for a moment.

946
00:39:25.883 --> 00:39:28.184
(sighs)

947
00:39:29.721 --> 00:39:30.853
Let's have him.

948
00:39:36.027 --> 00:39:37.960
Commissioner.

949
00:39:38.029 --> 00:39:39.829
Inspector.

950
00:39:39.897 --> 00:39:40.897
Sid.

951
00:39:40.965 --> 00:39:42.431
Sully.

952
00:39:44.202 --> 00:39:46.402
Kimura. it was nothing personal.

953
00:39:48.906 --> 00:39:51.073
Congratulations.

954
00:39:58.783 --> 00:40:00.783
Thank you. Sully.

955
00:40:21.873 --> 00:40:23.806
It's just not right.

956
00:40:31.916 --> 00:40:34.016
I'll see you in court.

957
00:40:39.223 --> 00:40:41.190
(door closes)

958
00:40:50.768 --> 00:40:51.967
And then?

959
00:40:52.036 --> 00:40:53.402
FRANK:
Then.

960
00:40:53.471 --> 00:40:55.004
you walk up to the mayor.

961
00:40:55.073 --> 00:40:57.073
and she presents you
with your new shield.

962
00:40:57.141 --> 00:40:59.241
You turn and shake my hand.

963
00:40:59.310 --> 00:41:02.278
and exit via the stage
to the left.

964
00:41:03.614 --> 00:41:06.415
Got it. Ready when you are.

965
00:41:06.484 --> 00:41:08.717
Shall we?

966
00:41:08.786 --> 00:41:10.719
I'm right behind you.

967
00:41:13.658 --> 00:41:15.591
(door opens)

968
00:41:16.994 --> 00:41:19.428
(door closes)

969
00:41:19.497 --> 00:41:21.363
(sighs)

970
00:41:21.432 --> 00:41:23.365
♪ ♪

971
00:41:33.177 --> 00:41:35.111
(exhales shakily)

972
00:41:45.053 --> 00:41:52.053
